3. Compiling and installing Websh (Unix)
----------------------------------------

Please note that we use some GNU make extensions, so make sure that 
you try to compile Websh using a GNU version of make (or gmake) when
compiling under UNIX.

Websh is a pure Tcl extension, Tk is not required. You need
Tcl 8.6 or newer (threaded build) to compile and install Websh 3.7.4.

typically:

  cd src/unix
  autoconf
  ./configure --with-tcl=/path/to/tcl/lib
  make
  make test
  make install

Make will create three targets: websh3.7.4, which is the standalone
Websh application (dynamically linked to Tcl and libwebsh3.7.4.so)
and libwebsh3.7.4.so, which is a TEA (Tcl Extension Architecture)
compliant shared object that can be dynamically loaded from within Tcl
using [load libwebsh3.7.4.so]. Both provide the Tcl package websh.
The third target is mod_websh3.7.4.so (the Apache module), which is
built automatically when Apache headers are found.

Apache headers and APR/APU include paths are detected automatically.
If they are not in a standard location, specify them explicitly:

  ./configure --with-tcl=/usr/local/tcl86/lib \
      --with-httpdinclude=/path/to/apache/include \
      --with-aprinclude=/path/to/apr/include

To build without the Apache module:

  ./configure --with-tcl=/usr/local/tcl86/lib --disable-apache

By default, Websh is installed to /usr/local
To change this location, provide the --prefix option to configure:

  ./configure --prefix=/opt


4. mod_websh: Websh as Apache Module
------------------------------------

Websh applications can both run in CGI mode and in mod_websh, the
module for Apache 2.4. mod_websh is built automatically when Apache
headers are found during configure. It requires a threaded Tcl build
(the default for most Tcl 8.6 installations).

Note: mod_websh is not compatible with mod_http2. Disable mod_http2
in the Apache configuration when using mod_websh.

mod_websh3.7.4.so is compiled by default when 'make all' is invoked
and Apache headers are available.

In order to use mod_websh in your Apache web server, please refer
to the file doc/mod_websh/README

A sample setup to serve SSI-type HTML with Websh-snipplets and CGI-type
scripts is found in doc/mod_websh and will be installed with the 
'make install' command.


5. Compiling and installing Websh and mod_websh (Windows XP)
------------------------------------------------------------

Websh currently provides a Makefile for Microsoft Visual Studio 6.0 nmake.

Please refer to the file src/win/README for details.


6. Support
----------

For support please try the following mailing list on tcl.apache.org:

  websh-user@tcl.apache.org

You may subscribe by sending mail to websh-user-subscribe@tcl.apache.org.

If you would like to contribute to websh, please subscribe to:

  websh-dev@tcl.apache.org

by sending mail to websh-dev-subscribe@tcl.apache.org.

In addition, Netcetera is committed to provide additional support for Websh.

You can reach us at

  support@websh.com

and

  info@websh.com


